os have been overcome, debt has been paid, and political and memorial correctness no longer serve as a muzzle; the young generation is repeatedly claimed to be the first which can accept German history without a sense of burden and speak freely about it. But is that really the case? Does not a sense of unease with the past still exist? Off the beaten path of academic literary studies, Kirstin Frieden examines the formats of different media segments such as performances, comedy, and new media (e.g., Facebook and YouTube). She shows evidence of new ways of talking about the Holocaust as well as a culture of memory that media-transforms the existing memory paradigm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCollective memory and literature. 0aCollective memoryzGermany. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945xPsychological aspects. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPsychological aspects. 0aMemoryxPolitical aspectszGermany. 4aErinnerungskultur. 4aGedächtnis. 4aGedächtnisparadigma. 4aGeneration. 4aJudentum. 4aJüdische Studien. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aMemorial Correctness. 4aPolitical Correctness. 4aSoziale Medien. 4aZeitgeschichte. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aContemporary History.  aCultural History.  aCultural Studies.  aJewish Studies.  aJudaism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2014z9783110370416oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Complete eBook Package 2014-2016z9783110489842oZDB-23-TGP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript: Complete eBook-Package 2014z9783110401226oZDB-23-TGP40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839426272zCo-access